Collapsible Archery Quiver
Easy for storage
Holds 6 Arrows Update - 28-11-17
Models updated to have rod holes carry on through all bodies.
Encased nut hole added in base.

In addition to the 3 printed parts
You will need:
2x lengths of 5mm Threaded rod cut to required length (mine was around 3/4 - 4/5s of the length of the arrows I was using
4x M5 Dome headed nuts - for top and bottom of quiver
16x M5 standard nuts - to stop each of the parts sliding down the rod (2 were used to act as a locking nut to prevent them undoing
2x D Shackle (found at most hardware stores
Some form of lanyard to preferred length - I made a paracord lanyard which worked very well as you can see from the picture I used an old keyring clip to attach it to my belt loop but other methods maybe better I actually placed a small ball of Sugru in the bottom of each of the tubes in the bottom part of the quiver and let it set so there is a cushion at the bottom to prevent the arrow smashing out the underside of the printed part. If you have any comments about the item or ways it could be improved please let me know as id like to know what you think.

description.text: I had been having trouble getting my roomba to dock without smashing the docking station around the room. Half of the time it would dock fine, but the other half of the time I would come home and find the roomba would have pushed the charger under a table or in to the room and then run out of battery and was just sitting there. Because of the carpet I couldn't stick the charger down, and eventually I worked out that I could use a clip and some double sided tape and hold it against the wall.

I am exploring the use of 3d printing to make holds for a climbing wall I am building. While it would be possible to directly print holds this is not optimal for several reasons. In order to be strong enough most holds would need to be printed of a high strength material (ABS at minimum, but optimally nylon or PET) and they would need to be printed at 100% infill. But high strength materials are notoriously difficult to print in big blocks and high infills. Even if the print could be accomplished it would be extremely time consuming and very expensive. Climbing walls need a lot of holds so directly printing them one at a time just isn't the best solution. Climbing hold producers cast their holds from resin, typically polyurethane. It would be possible to print a master from and make a mold from it. However, mold rubber is quite expensive and the mold making process is time consuming, and with a little 3d printed cleverness it can be avoided. It is easier to turn the master into a mold digitally and then print the mold in a flexible material. Ninjaflex would work great because it is very stretchy and flexy which are are good characteristics in a mold. But those characteristics make it difficult to print reliably. It is also proprietary and quite expensive. TPU filament is slightly stiffer which makes it much easier to print. Plus it is available from multiple suppliers thus it is much cheaper. The socket in the middle of the mold forms the countersink for the mounting bolt. The socket holds a stub of 3/8" round rod which forms the bolt hole. It would be possible to print this part of the mold but in practice it doesn't work well. Since the 3/8" round has a relatively small cross section it tends to tear off on the first cast. The example shown is based on a model of a human brain made from a medical scan and somewhat simplified to make a usable mold. The photo shows a hold cast in high strength fiber-reinforced industrial grout. This material is very inexpensive and It works great for large holds like this where its lack of tensile strength isn't an issue. Smaller holds and designs where part of the hold must resist tension are better cast in a polyurethane resin such as Alumilite RC-3. RC-3 sets so quickly that you can mix, pour and unmold a cast every 10-15 minutes. For comparison printing this hold at 100% infill would take 48 hours if it could be done at all. We talked about this and a whole lot more on the 3D Printing Today podcast available on iTunes, or Stitcher radio learn more at http://www.threedprintingtoday.com/

description.text:
This is a set of dials for counting things in games. I used the small ones as wound counters in things like Warhammer or Kings of War. I also use the large ones for that, but they also make great Magic The Gathering life counters.
This design is laser cut using 2 pieces of material, probably fairly thin (I used 1/16" acrylic) and a few 1/8" (or 3mm) cylindrical rare earth magnets. Each disk gets a magnet in the hole in the center which allows the disks to stay together and rotate freely.
There are several ways to deal with the numbers. You can do a raster etching onto some types of plastic. I wanted more contrast so I covered the surface of my material with masking tape and did a vector cut around the stroke of the numbers on a lower setting (17% power, 100% speed, 5000 freq on a 75W Epilog) and peeled the tape of the numbers themselves away and airbrushed it.
These things are really handy, and if you set the magnets correctly you can make them interchangeable and very easily stackable.

title: Improved Snap On Guide for "|Robert|'s Alternative UM2 Feeder V2"

description.text:
This is an updated version of the snap on guide for |Robert|'s Alternative UM2 Feeder V2.
I created it after I tried to use this feeder for 1.75mm filament and found that it needs some additional guidance under the extruder motor. While printing test prints with the new feeder and 2.85mm filament I also had some noise coming from the feeder which has its cause by the filament not really centered on the pressure bearing. So I adapted the addtional guidance for the 2.85mm version too. With those two pieces I can switch the extruder from 2.85 to 1.75 just by switching the snap on guide. I tested the 2.85 with some prints, works perfectly, noise is completely gone.
The 1.75 I only tested that the feeding really works, I want to change the bowden tube, the PTFE coupler and the nozzle before I do my first print. Maybe this gets an updated after the first print, but so far it looks very good. NOTE: This could be called version 2, I withdrew the first one as I experienced filament grinding with the 2.85 version. I realized that the additional guidance caused this because the filament is too strong to be bent enough on the resulting 1cm between the guides where the extruder and the pressure bearing are if the filament can not move a bit. So I changed the round hole to long holes because only the position of the filament centered on the wheels is important.

title: Rostock MAX top mount spool holder

description.text: A free rolling low profile top mount spool holder for the Rostock MAX. I was trying to design something that would take minimal torque away from the extruder to spin the spool. I had some MR105ZZ bearings sitting around from another project, so I designed this around using them... And it works great! Used in conjunction with my EZstruder top mount: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:119198 UPDATE: All files should be printable and work together now. I was having issues with the "spool_hub_base" & "toner_plastics_spool_center" not screwing together, but adjusted the sizes and all is well now! If you've downloaded before 7/21/2013 please re-download those 2 files or they won't screw together properly

I used KISSlicer with 0.2mm layers, and 2 perimeters, 1.1mm skin thickness using a .5 nozzle You'll need:
3 MR105ZZ bearings
1 30mm M3 screw
2 M3 nuts
3 M3 washers

  • Print all plastic parts, and 3 of the bearing_pins & bearing_keepers. These are just pins with c-clips (keepers), you can use screws but I didn't have any short enough so I made these.

  • Put the bearings into the slots on the underside of the round spool plate, and secure them with the bearing pins (or screws).

  • The spool holder attached to the top plate using a 30mm M3 socket cap screw. Place 1 M3 washer above the large round holder, then under an M3 nut, then M3 washer. Set this on into one of the holes in the top plate. Adjust the nut position on the screw until there is just a little bit of "play" with the socket cap above the round plate, don't want it too tight or it won't spin freely. Refer to the pictures if this sounds confusing :)

  • Next place a washer then nut under the top plate to secure it to the top plate & tighten to keep it in place. However not super tight or you'll crush the melamine

  • Make sure to print the "spool_hub_base" with the tabs pointed up or it probably won't do too well. This just snaps into the round spool holder, be careful though to not break the tabs off. Some sanding (or knife scraping) may be necessary to get them to go in properly because it's a tight fit.

  • Screw the "toner_plastics_spool_center" onto the spool hub base. If your spool has a different center diameter, you can modify the "toner_plastics_spool_center.scad" file and modify the "spoolInnerDiameter" variable at the top of the file to match your spool diameter, re-compile & render, then export the new STL & print. I made them this way in case you have different spools from different manufacturers, that way you can easily unscrew and swap out the center pieces. :) If you don't feel like going through that the spool will probably just rest on top without a center printed because there not much lateral force anyway, it will probably just spin as the extruder pulls on it. There's less friction to cause it to turn than there would be to cause it to drag across the round spool holder platform.

title: Blower Fan Duct for MTW Minimax

description.text:
This is a print cooling fan upgrade for the MTW Minimax. You'll need to swap out the 40mm axial fan that comes with the kit for a 4020 (40mm x 20mm) blower fan, which are cheap as chips. The duct encircles the printer nozzle and ensures air is delivered to all sides of the nozzle exactly where it is needed without cooling the heater block. An internal vane helps equalise the air pressure on all sides of the nozzle. Designed to be printed from ABS without supports. You will need one of each printed part. In addition to those you will need;
  • 1 x 4020 Centrifugal (blower) fan
  • 2x M3 x 30mm bolts with nut
  • 1 x M3 x 25mm bolt with nut* (longer is fine)
  • 1 x M3 x 40mm bolt with nut* (longer is fine)
    • *Nyloc nuts are ideal but not necessary. Once printed, assembly should be fairly straight forward. Refer to my photo if you're having difficulty.
    If it isn't already, turn your hotend so that the connected wires faces toward the rear of the printer and pass through the notch in the duct. The 25mm and 40mm long bolts are used to secure the assembly to the Y carriage, whilst the two 30mm long bolts are used through the uppermost holes in the fan. Once installed, you may (most likely will) find that the original Y end stop prevents the carriage from moving all the way home. The included replacement mount will fix this. Reuse the screws from the original Y end stop. You won't need those pesky teeny M2 nuts as it is designed to take a thread.

title: Upgraded X-carriage for Sunhokey Prusa i3 - Integrated fans, 20mm extra Z-range and PiBot optical height sensor.

description.text:
EDIT - 29.11.2015
Added a dual extrusion version by request. There is slight room for height adjustment at the neck clamp. I will not print and use this yet as I have no plans for dual extrusion on this printer. Let me know if there's a problem with it. It assembles in CAD. The center-to center distance is 26 mm.

EDIT - 24.11.2015 I made new fan holder/clamp parts because the old ones were flawed and clamped the hot end at an angle. The new ones also look much better. If you want to print fast try adding my lightweight bearing blocks: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1149490

The Sunhokey Prusa i3 carriage is not very well designed. It prevents the printer from taking full advantage of the Z-range, has a filmsy hot end mount and and does not have integrated fan mounts, so I made a new one. This carriage is made for three bearings to prevent rocking. There is a pocket for mounting a PiBot optical height sensor (http://www.pibot.com/pibot-optical-reflection-endstop-rev143.html) which works really well as a Z-endstop to achieve perfect bed height every time. It can also be used like this as a bed leveling sensor. There's also a fan duct which guides the cold end fan air over the fins, and mounting posts for 35x10 mm blower fans. I included a fan duct without the blower posts as well. The hoop for the belt ends is positioned better than the stock assembly, so the belt stays parallel.

For the Pibot sensor to work, it needs to always move down towards the bed, and a simple G-code sequence achieves this and height sensing accurately every time (so far at least). G91 ; Relative mode
G0 Z4 ; Lift 4mm to prepare the PiBot sensor <-This value MUST be larger than the "current height" value below.
G90 ; Absolute mode
G28 ; Home all axes
G92 Z3.6 ; Set current height <- replace 3.6 with whatever height the PiBot sensor ends up at. You need to measure this and test print to see if it's accurate.

Carrier01 - The actual carriage.
Carrier02 - The clamp with integrated fan duct and blower posts.
Carrier03 - The clamp without blower posts.
Carrier04 - The hoop for attaching the belt ends.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Notes: Print in the orientations the models open in. If the back of Carrier01.stl warps you can compensate with washers when you assemble.

title: Robo R1 TR8 Lead Screw / Coupling Upgrade

description.text:
For people who experience Z Axis ribbing and want a cheaper alternative to the "Official" Robo3D Z Axis upgrade, here is what you need. Print two copies of the model presented here. It is an adapter that will take a brass leadscrew nut and adapt it to fit the hexagon opening of the Robo3D X Idler. There is a very slight taper to the hex to help minimize backlash. With the adapter in place there is no loss of Z axis build height and the Auto-level still functions as normal. Although it is designed to be a pressure fit on the leadscrew nut, you should also use four M3 x 8 mm (#4 x 3/8" equivalent) self tapping screws to secure the nut in place. At the same time this adapter also replaces the Auto-level Stabilizers that are used to attach the Z Axis leveling microswitches. Use two M2.5 x 8 mm (#2 x 3/8" equivalent) self tapping screws to attach the microswitches to the adapter. Additionally you should also replace the flexible motor shaft couplings with solid couplings. You will need two couplings that are designed with a 5 mm bore on one end and an 8 mm bore on the other.

Picture for illustration purposes only In addition you will also need two pieces of TR8*8 Leadscrews and accompanying Leadscrew Nuts. Length should be about 350 - 300 mm. This was created to provide a readily available alternative to the Robo Upgrade and to make installation as simple as possible. You do not need to remove any wiring or stepper motors in this process. Disassembly of your Robo is kept to a minimum. Also the chances are reduced of receiving a bent lead screw without the integrated stepper. Multiple versions of the source files are included if you need to modify the dimensions slightly (STEP, SAT & SMT).

I would suggest using a filament that has a lower coefficient of friction such as PETG or Nylon. Verify that all measurements are correct, as this is a model designed to be pressure fit together. Proper extruder calibration should be done prior to printing these parts.

Required Hardware
  • 2 - TR8*8 Lead Screw and Nut Assemblies 300 - 350 mm length
  • 2 - Solid Motor Couplings w/ 5 mm and 8 mm bores
  • 4 - M2.5 x 8 mm Self-Tapping Machine Screws
  • 8 - M3 x 8 mm Self-Tapping Machine Screws (Optional)
    • Firmware Modification
    Please note that the following entry in Marlin Configuration.h must be changed:
    #define DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT {80,80,2560,723.38}
    The value of the third parameter (2650) needs to be changed to the following:
    #define DEFAULT_AXIS_STEPS_PER_UNIT {80,80,400,723.38} The value listed above is for the most commonly available lead screw TR8*8. One complete rotation moves the Z axis 8 mm. If you have a lead screw with any other movement dimension, please use the Prusa calculators to find the appropriate value for your particular needs. The calculator is located at the following link, Reprap lead screw step calculator

17 Sept 2016, increased taper on hexagonal section to make sliding into X-Axis bracket easier. moved micro-switches up an additional 0.1 mm to ensure engagement.
14 Dec 2015, moved the screw holes for the microswitch up 0.2 mm to make sure the top of the switch sits above the level of the flattened area. This change was to insure that the switch is depressed completely when in its normal position.
25 Nov 2015, increased the taper a bit to make sliding on easier. Please print then measure. If it doesn't fit snugly when inserted, then reprint increasing the scale just a bit. Now included IGES and Fusion 360 backup files.
Additional information may be found at the Robo3D forums located at http://community.robo3d.com/index.php
